831">I agree with you wholeheartedly. Since I lived through the "AIDS" decade of the 1980's, just about everyone, who actually had AIDS and not just HIV, died. I knew I was HIV+ from 1987 diagnosis, but in retrospect, I must have been infected in the late 1970's or in the early 1980's.<br /><br />I am basically a pessimist, but because my lover was diagnosed with AIDS in 1987, I was too busy taking care of him to worry about myself. I got on AZT (which was the only drug at the time), then got on with life. When he died in 1989, again I felt if it was my turn, it would happen. However, even before the internet, I read everything I could, I went to the HIV specialist every 3 months, ate well (which I've always done), worked out at the gym, but spend most of my time worrying about my job, not my health. When I read another drug was available (3tc) added to just the AZT regimen, I went with it. It saved my life.<br /><br />When I had the opportunity to be on an experimental drug (which turned out to be the protease inhibitor, Crixivan, I jumped at the chance. It was new and different, and kept me alive. Since then, I have changed my drug regimen to what the current "gold" standard was and is now.<br /><br />I am still a pessimist, but not about my HIV--just about life in general. I have never been a "positive thinker" but have never been a fatalist, either.<br /><br />If you had a usually terminal illness that you think "positive thinking" helped, then the best to you. If you had a usually terminal illness that you think "religion--any religion" helped, then the best to you. If you, like me, just took the best "scientific way" at the time and it helped you, then the best to you.<br /><br />As a pessimist, I doubt that "positive thinking" alone can will yourself out of a deadly disease. However, "positive thinking" plus sound medical advice may certainly help, and the best to you.<br /><br />There is a Buddhist saying, that translated into a Judeo-Christian context, states that we are not all meant to be Methuselah. Some die young; some die old and well; others die old and suffer. If you want to consider it fate, that's great. If you want to consider it chance, then roll the dice.<br /><br />We live, we love (hopefully), we sometimes suffer, and then we all die. While it is sorrowful for those of us still living, I don't think that the dead think of it in those terms. Those terms are human constructs, neither good nor bad.</dd> <dd class="tool clearfix"> <!--<a assetVoteId="" assetId="11627831" class="unlike needsReg">Unlike this</a>--> <!--<a assetVoteId="" assetId="11627831" class="like needsReg">Like this</a>--> <a class="mail toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="E-mail to a friend" messageid="11627831"></a> <a class="repo toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="Report offensive content" messageid="11627831"></a> <a class="link toolTipElement2" href="/8618-3445_162-57331654.html?assetTypeId=41&messageId=11627831&blogId=" title="Permalink to this comment"></a> <!--person likes--> <!--people like--> <!--<span class="liked"><b></b> this</span>--> </dd> <dd class="toolstretch"> <div id="emailAFriendArea_11627831"></div> <div id="emailAFriendStatus_11627831" class="newcommentstatus"></div> <div id="offensiveArea_11627831"></div> <div id="offensiveStatus_11627831" class="newcommentstatus"></div> </dd> </dl> <a name="11628418"></a> <dl messageid="11628418" class="thread"> <dt class="subj"></dt> <dt class="author"> <span>by <b>involved_indi</b></span> November 27, 2011 9:49 PM EST </dt> <dd id="body_11628418">The mind is extremely powerful. I recently seen a person with a de-gloved foot (industrial accident) in agony... actually go to sleep in a trauma center after they had been told that a nerve block was in place and their pain should go away. Shortly thereafter, the trauma surgeon discovered that the medecine for the block wasn't being delivered. The mind believed the pain was gone... so the pain was gone.</dd> <dd class="tool clearfix"> <!--<a assetVoteId="" assetId="11628418" class="unlike needsReg">Unlike this</a>--> <!--<a assetVoteId="" assetId="11628418" class="like needsReg">Like this</a>--> <a class="mail toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="E-mail to a friend" messageid="11628418"></a> <a class="repo toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="Report offensive content" messageid="11628418"></a> <a class="link toolTipElement2" href="/8618-3445_162-57331654.html?assetTypeId=41&messageId=11628418&blogId=" title="Permalink to this comment"></a> <!--person likes--> <!--people like--> <!--<span class="liked"><b></b> this</span>--> </dd> <dd class="toolstretch"> <div id="emailAFriendArea_11628418"></div> <div id="emailAFriendStatus_11628418" class="newcommentstatus"></div> <div id="offensiveArea_11628418"></div> <div id="offensiveStatus_11628418" class="newcommentstatus"></div> </dd> </dl> </dd> </dl> <!-- --> <a name="11627529"></a> <dl messageid="11627529"> <dt class="subj"></dt> <dt class="author"> <span>by <b>daoway</b></span> November 27, 2011 5:19 PM EST </dt> <dd id="body_11627529">Regarding whether positive thinking matters or doesn't, the science is not there yet to decide that definitively, so the reliance is on statistics, which can have built-in bias and interpretive variation. One thing we do know, stress does effect biology and does kill. It would seem astounding to find that it's opposite, well-being, happiness, and the parasympathetic nervous system has no effect, that the relaxation response is not vital to recovery and health. Statistics is a blunt instrument and entertaining, and useful for broad, high-level planning, but when it comes to individual patients it loses relevancy. Stay smiling, keep positive and look forward seem to be wise guidelines. Spirituality is also vital, as is prayer in my experience, and supports the parasympathetic nervous system. From a treatment and support point-of-view, hospitals, medical staff, family and friends can go a long way to help in recover by being positive, supportive and encouraging.</dd> <dd class="tool clearfix"> <!-- assetVote: --> <!-- logged in: --> <!-- remember me: --> <a class="reply needsReg">Reply to this comment</a> <a class="mail toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="E-mail to a friend"></a> <a class="repo toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="Report offensive content"></a> <a class="link toolTipElement2" href="/8618-3445_162-57331654.html?assetTypeId=41&messageId=11627529&blogId=" title="Permalink to this comment"></a> </dd> <dd class="toolstretch"><!-- --></dd> </dl> <!-- --> <a name="11627376"></a> <dl messageid="11627376"> <dt class="subj"></dt> <dt class="author"> <span>by <b>MarieBatt</b></span> November 27, 2011 4:11 PM EST </dt> <dd id="body_11627376">Of course you can't 'will' cancer - or any disease - out of existence, but you can make a difference on how you live the rest of your life. In essence we are all 'terminal' as any of us could die today or tomorrow....as Ingrid Bergman once said, "Cancer victims who don't accept their fate, who don't learn to live with it, will only destroy what little time they have left." So the important thing is to make the most of today and still plan on having a tomorrow.</dd> <dd class="tool clearfix"> <!-- assetVote: --> <!-- logged in: --> <!-- remember me: --> <a class="reply needsReg">Reply to this comment</a> <a class="mail toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="E-mail to a friend"></a> <a class="repo toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="Report offensive content"></a> <a class="link toolTipElement2" href="/8618-3445_162-57331654.html?assetTypeId=41&messageId=11627376&blogId=" title="Permalink to this comment"></a> </dd> <dd class="toolstretch"><!-- --></dd> <dd class="replieswrapper"> <a name="11628603"></a> <dl messageid="11628603" class="thread"> <dt class="subj"></dt> <dt class="author"> <span>by <b>peedo5</b></span> November 27, 2011 10:43 PM EST </dt> <dd id="body_11628603">I think this is a very good way to approach it, who wants to make themselves even more miserable, why not make the most out the one life we have?</dd> <dd class="tool clearfix"> <!--<a assetVoteId="" assetId="11628603" class="unlike needsReg">Unlike this</a>--> <!--<a assetVoteId="" assetId="11628603" class="like needsReg">Like this</a>--> <a class="mail toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="E-mail to a friend" messageid="11628603"></a> <a class="repo toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="Report offensive content" messageid="11628603"></a> <a class="link toolTipElement2" href="/8618-3445_162-57331654.html?assetTypeId=41&messageId=11628603&blogId=" title="Permalink to this comment"></a> <!--person likes--> <!--people like--> <!--<span class="liked"><b></b> this</span>--> </dd> <dd class="toolstretch"> <div id="emailAFriendArea_11628603"></div> <div id="emailAFriendStatus_11628603" class="newcommentstatus"></div> <div id="offensiveArea_11628603"></div> <div id="offensiveStatus_11628603" class="newcommentstatus"></div> </dd> </dl> </dd> </dl> <!-- --> <a name="11627166"></a> <dl messageid="11627166"> <dt class="subj"></dt> <dt class="author"> <span>by <b>MacDerb</b></span> November 27, 2011 2:43 PM EST </dt> <dd id="body_11627166">Positive thinking works extremely well.
<br />However, it cannot be overdone or some may rightly conclude that it is false. The smile on the faces of Wallace &#38; Grommit (who I love) are overdone.
<br />
<br />Positive reinforcement is essential to the development of children during their formitive years. However, in the United States corporal punishment reigns supreme as law of the land to my dissent.
<br />
<br />Nevertheless, positive thinking should never be confused with positive law, as the two are separate and unequal. It should not be confused with positivism a sociological theory.
<br />
<br />Being generally positive can help society overcome poor attitudes and promote resolve in most instances. Pair it with listening power - actual listening, not half-hearted with one eye on the television listening and you've got a good friend.
<br />
<br />I've seen positive thinking happen in the United States. I'll exit on that positive note.</dd> <dd class="tool clearfix"> <!-- assetVote: --> <!-- logged in: --> <!-- remember me: --> <a class="reply needsReg">Reply to this comment</a> <a class="mail toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="E-mail to a friend"></a> <a class="repo toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="Report offensive content"></a> <a class="link toolTipElement2" href="/8618-3445_162-57331654.html?assetTypeId=41&messageId=11627166&blogId=" title="Permalink to this comment"></a> </dd> <dd class="toolstretch"><!-- --></dd> </dl> <!-- --> <a name="11627152"></a> <dl messageid="11627152"> <dt class="subj"></dt> <dt class="author"> <span>by <b>ccfsdca</b></span> November 27, 2011 2:38 PM EST </dt> <dd id="body_11627152">i have personally known 6 people (family, friends, friends' family members etc) over the past 30 years including teenager who stated, 'i'm gonna beat this' but didn't. my sister-in-law is the latest and isn't expected to be here for xmas. i believe the positive thinking can help life be better while still here but i don't believe it has anything at all to do with who actually lives or doesn't and frankly, i think it does a disservice to those who are keeping a positive attitude but die -- there's the suggestion that somehow they didn't 'fight hard enough' or weren't 'strong enough' to make the difference with their attitude.</dd> <dd class="tool clearfix"> <!-- assetVote: --> <!-- logged in: --> <!-- remember me: --> <a class="reply needsReg">Reply to this comment</a> <a class="mail toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="E-mail to a friend"></a> <a class="repo toolTipElement2 needsReg" title="Report offensive content"></a> <a class="link toolTipElement2" href="/8618-3445_162-57331654.html?assetTypeId=41&messageId=11627152&blogId=" title="Permalink to this comment"></a> </dd> <dd class="toolstretch"><!-- --></dd> </dl> <ul class="pagination"> <li class="youAreHere">1</li> <li><a href="/8601-3445_162-573